        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9765.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Daniel Oliver, 19 December 1874</ref> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 22).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In his letter of 19 December 1874, Oliver had written, ‘It is too bad to talk of asking “favours”!’.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Oliver had sent CD specimens of <hi rend="italic">Genlisea</hi> (the corkscrew plant), from the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, in December 1874 (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 22, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9778.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Daniel Oliver, 24 December 1874</ref>. <hi rend="italic">Utricularia montana</hi> is a synonym of <hi rend="italic">U. alpina</hi>, the alpine bladderwort. CD discussed <hi rend="italic">G. ornata</hi>, <hi rend="italic">G. africana</hi>, <hi rend="italic">G. aurea</hi>, and <hi rend="italic">G. filiformis</hi> in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4097.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi></ref>, pp. 446–52.</note>
        </div>        
            
